'''Allen Henry Vigneron, [[Ph.D.]], [[Licentiate of Sacred Theology|S.T.L.]]''' (born October 21, 1948) is an [[United States|American]] [[prelate]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]]. He is the current [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Detroit|Archbishop of Detroit]] and [[Roman Catholic Mission Sui Iuris of Cayman Islands|Ecclesiastical Superior of the Cayman Islands]], having previously served as [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Oakland|Bishop of Oakland]] from 2003 to 2009.<ref name="TheCompass01092009"/>

==Biography==
===Early life===
The eldest of six children, Allen Vigneron was born in [[Mount Clemens, Michigan|Mount Clemens]], [[Michigan]],<ref name="TheCompass01092009"/> to Elwin and Bernardine (n<U+00E9>e Kott) Vigneron. He is of French descent on his father's side and German on his mother's.<ref>[http://www.linternaute.com/dictionnaire/fr/definition/vigneron Vigneron profile]</ref> He graduated from [[Sacred Heart Major Seminary]] in 1970, receiving degrees in both [[Philosophy]] and [[Classical language|Classical Languages]]. He then furthered his studies at the [[Pontifical Gregorian University]] in [[Rome]], where he obtained a [[Bachelor of Sacred Theology|Bachelor's degree in Sacred Theology]] in 1973.

===Priesthood===
Upon his return to the [[United States]], Vigneron was [[Holy Orders|ordained]] to the [[Priesthood (Catholic Church)|priesthood]] by Cardinal [[John Francis Dearden]] on July 26, 1975.<ref name="TheCompass01092009"/> He then served as associate [[Curate|pastor]] of Our Lady Queen of Peace Church in [[Harper Woods, Michigan|Harper Woods]]. He earned his [[Licentiate in Sacred Theology]] from the Gregorian in 1977, and later resumed his [[Parish (Catholic Church)|pastoral]] work in suburban [[Detroit]].

Vigneron completed his graduate studies at the [[The Catholic University of America|Catholic University of America]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], earning his [[Doctor of Philosophy|doctorate in philosophy]] in 1987 with a [[Thesis|dissertation]] on [[Edmund Husserl]]. He was also made a [[professor]] (1985) and the [[Dean (education)|dean]] (1988) of Sacred Heart Seminary. From 1991 to 1994, Vigneron served as an official in the [[Secretariat of State (Holy See)|Vatican Secretariat of State]] and adjunct instructor at the Gregorian. He then returned to Sacred Heart Seminary as its [[Rector (academia)|Rector]]. Vigneron, who was raised by [[Pope John Paul II]] to the rank of [[Monsignor]] in 1994,<ref name="TheCompass01092009"/> removed several teachers from the seminary for having strayed from official church doctrine in his opinion.<ref name=detroit>{{cite news|title=Archbishop-designate Vigneron aims to defend teachings, build harmony|date=2009-01-27|publisher=Detroit Free Press| url=http://www.freep.com/article/20090127/NEWS05/901270373?imw=Y|accessdate=2009-01-28}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

===Episcopate===
On June 12, 1996, Vigneron was appointed [[Auxiliary Bishop]] of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Detroit|Detroit]] and [[Titular Bishop]] of ''[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Sault Sainte Marie, Michigan|Sault Sainte Marie in Michigan]]''. He received his [[Bishop (Catholic Church)|episcopal consecration]] on the following July 9 from Cardinal [[Adam Maida]], with [[James Aloysius Hickey|Cardinals James Hickey]] and [[Edmund Szoka]] serving as [[Consecrator|co-consecrators]]. Vigneron was later named [[Coadjutor Bishop]] of [[Oakland, California|Oakland]], [[California]], on January 10, 2003, succeeding [[John Stephen Cummins]] as the third [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Oakland|Bishop of Oakland]] on October 1 of that same year.<ref name="TheCompass01092009"/> In California, he helped lead protests against [[same-sex marriage]].<ref>[http://articles.sfgate.com/2003-01-18/bay-area/17473442_1_catholic-seminaries-catholic-colleges-bishop-john-cummins SFGate: "New Oakland bishop called conservative"]</ref> He compared [[abortion]] and [[Stem cell controversy|stem-cell research]] to [[slavery]] and [[racism]].<ref name=detroit/>

[[Pope Benedict XVI]] appointed Vigneron [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Detroit|Archbishop of Detroit]] on January 5, 2009, replacing longtime incumbent Cardinal Maida.<ref name="TheCompass01092009">{{cite news|title=Cardinal Maida retires; successor named|date=January 9, 2009|publisher=The Compass (official publication of the Catholic Diocese of Green Bay, Wisconsin)|accessdate=2009-01-13}}</ref> Installed on January 28, 2009, Vigneron is the first metropolitan Detroit native named Archbishop of Detroit.<ref name="TheCompass01092009"/> He was elected [[Chair (official)|chairman]] of the [[Board of Trustees of The Catholic University of America]] on June 9, 2009. He received the [[pallium]], a [[vestment]] worn by [[metropolitan bishop]]s, from Benedict XVI on June 29, 2009 in a ceremony at [[St. Peter's Basilica]]. On April 21, 2011, as Archbishop of Detroit, he participated in an [http://www.pressandguide.com/articles/2011/04/21/news/doc4db0cf5992299756736717.txt?viewmode=2 interfaith vigil] held at the [[Islamic Center of America]] in [[Dearborn, Michigan]]. 

